article.headline: Bucks continue high-scoring ways
article.story:
MILWAUKEE (AP) -- Scott Skiles has been stressing defense since becoming coach of the Chicago Bulls. His message was not received Friday night. Michael Redd scored 30 points and Damon Jones added a season-high 22, helping the Milwaukee Bucks send Chicago to its fourth consecutive loss, 109-95 Friday night. Milwaukee, the Eastern Conference's highest scoring team, blew a 16-point first-half lead but used a late 16-2 run to drop the Bulls to 1-4 since Skiles became coach Dec. 1. It was the first time Chicago gave up 100 points since Skiles arrived. "I have to set the tone that the guys understand that if you aren't out there playing as hard as you can on the defensive end, there will be a consequence for that," Skiles said. "It's just something we are still learning and we have to work on." With the score tied at 87, Dan Gadzuric scored on a rebound to give Milwaukee the lead for good with 5:29 to go. Jamal Crawford scored on a fast-break layup with 2:48 left to pull Chicago to 95-89, but Milwaukee scored the next eight points. "The guys just never quit," said Milwaukee coach Terry Porter, whose team matched its season high in points. "Chicago did a great job of coming back at us, but we refused to lose the game." Chicago is 5-16 and has dropped seven consecutive road games. "I was frustrated a long time ago, but it is reaching a point where it is becoming unbearable for me," guard Kendall Gill said. "With Scottie (Pippen) gone, it is making things worse. But, I'm keeping my head up along with my teammates. The only way from here is up." Desmond Mason had 21 points, 11 rebounds and seven assists for the Bucks, which had a season-high 35 assists on their 44 field goals. Mason has started the past eight games in place of injured Tim Thomas, averaging 17 points the last seven games. "When you're out on the court at the beginning of the game you're able to get into the game a little quicker," Mason said. Marcus Fizer scored a season-high 19 points, Kendall Gill added 18 and rookie Kirk Hinrich had a career-high 17 for Chicago. "Ever since the coaching change, the way we play, the comfort level has been a lot different," Hinrich said. "I've been feeling a lot better out there." Hinrich scored 13 points in the third quarter, including the final eight of the period, to bring Chicago within 80-76 going into the fourth quarter. Fizer's free throw capped a 13-0 run and put Chicago ahead 81-80 with 10:02 left. Milwaukee made 15 of 23 shots to open a 31-15 lead after one quarter. Chicago got within 44-36 in the second quarter, but Milwaukee led 57-46 at halftime behind Redd's 15 points.

Game notes
Pippen will miss six weeks after surgery Friday revealed a torn meniscus in his left knee. ... Bulls F Corie Blount missed the game with a medial collateral sprain and is questionable for Saturday night's game vs. Indiana. ... A moment of silence was held before the game to honor longtime Milwaukee TV sports broadcaster Earl Gillespie, who died Friday at age 81. ... Skiles was whistled for his first technical foul with Chicago for arguing a call in the second quarter.
